snippet.textDisplay: Although SARS-CoV-2 is a big big problem, H1N1 (the "Spanish" flu from 1918-1919) infected roughly two-thirds of the total human population and killed roughly 10% of them during its big outbreak. Practically the entire world is working on trying to prevent SARS-CoV-2 from getting that kind of spread. You can do your part to help this global effort by avoiding contact with other people or objects other people would touch, washing your hands a lot, not touching your face, and just plain staying home unless you absolutely have to leave home for a legitimately important reason.
snippet.textOriginal: Although *SARS-CoV-2 is a big big problem,* H1N1 (the "Spanish" flu from 1918-1919) infected _roughly two-thirds of the total human population_ and _killed roughly 10% of them_ during its big outbreak. Practically the entire world is working on trying to prevent SARS-CoV-2 from getting that kind of spread. You can do your part to help this global effort by avoiding contact with other people or objects other people would touch, washing your hands a lot, not touching your face, and just plain staying home unless you _absolutely have_ to leave home for a _legitimately important_ reason.
